config.description: Grouping by model vs human and deduplication

data.output: The was an oil spill in the park. Petrol, diesel and other flammible liquids from the nearby fuel station had seeped into the ground and were bubbling up between the cracks. Some suggested using big sponges to remove it, but in the end a pump was brought which was able to suck away most of the liquid.

The industrial space ship landed on the docks next to a industrial scale pump, one of many in the area. The planet was one massive resource for petrol and diesel, covered in oil pumps and refineries. The crew of the space ship would spent the next five days here whilst its cargo containers were filled and then they would make the return journey across the milky way back to Earth, transporting their liquid gold back to those that required it fror

For his next mission, special agent Frank Tomlinson would require a vehicle with a unique modification. In order to arrange this, he went to see his underground mechanic Diesel Dan, who told him that the modification would be difficult, but that he could do it for £100,000. 'When did you pump up the price?', Frank asked, 'last time it was only eighty-thousand!', but Dan pretended not to hear him as he carried on sorting his various barrels of petrol. After handing over the money, Diesel Dan completed the modification and Frank was ready for his mission.

It was a sunny day and little Mia's favourite place to play was next to the old pink water pump hidden in the wildflowers at her grandma's house. At only 6 years old, she didn't quite know what it was but had painted, decorated and pretended it was magic for as long as she could remember. Her grandma would tell her of the days when the big petrol and diesel trucks would come rolling through the town but Mia wasn't interested in the history, only in the fantasy worlds she could create in her beautiful hideout.

And then she woke up from the dream, or some would call it a nightmare. She was at a Just Stop Oil protest, dressed as a petrol pump, spewing diesel on those who did not believe that we were having an ecological crisis. After her victims were thoroughly soaked she lit them on fire, their screams adding a sparkle to her eyes.

I made it a few miles down the road before I heard that terrible noise. The car rolled to a stop by the side of the road and I realised my mistake. I'd put diesel in my petrol car! They were right beside each other at the pump. Now the long wait for the recovery man, how embarrassing!

Off on my holidays to the Carribean. As i left the plane door the smell of the diesel in the air is a sign that I was about to have fun. Off on the roads and watching the numerous mopeds speeding along. they are zigzagging in and out of traffic and pedestrians. No wonder there are lots of petrol patches on the roads from accidents. Oh my!! these cases are heavy, good job  I went to the gym to pump up my muscles.

During one night at my local gym i bumped into Vin Diesel who commented on my abilty to lift my weight correctly. He decided to show me a better way to get my pump on. Whilst given the chance to ask him, i quipped if he had any siblings named after petrol.

In the mysterious post-apocalyptic land of "Mechanica" there was a severe shortage of petrol. The robots were starting to squeak at the hinges, and the leaders of Mechanica were starting to panic. They heard through the digital grapevine that there may be a way to drill and pump for a new type of digital diesel called "Digisel". However, their usual digital hacker (a robot named Bill) was pretty much keeling over thanks to the petrol shortage, and the codes to access the mystery digital product were looking to be inaccessible.

As I walked along the ruined banks of the polluted river, the stench of diesel was almost overpowering. The devastation of this habitat since the pump had malfunctioned and spewed waste was almost complete. I could have wept in memory of the past beauty that was lost. The glorious verdant and lush vegetation, the dazzling colours of the flowers; even the flash of the petrol blue feathers of a rare kingfisher.

I was driving my petrol lawnmower whilst maintaining my 3 acres of fields. In a lapse of judgement I accidentally crashed into a water pump that irrigated the farm. Whilst the pump was being repaired, I had to hire a diesel generator to replace the pump.

Laurel and Dan were driving through a town in their new diesel car. It was a nice town, where people were extremely welcoming and happy. They stopped at the local inn and found themselves in the company of some lovely ladies. They were offered free drinks and they found a nice hot meal to warm their bodies. Ahh, but it was time to go since they couldn't be there forever. Little did they know that they were stuck there. the locals needed gas to prepare their meal, so they used a pump to suck all the petrol out of their car. Luckly, they had some horses they could exchange for the car, if they could tame them.

I was driving down the highway, on my way to visit my uncle at his farm when i decided to pull over and take a break. I ran into the shop to grab some food and drink as I still had a few hours to go before reaching the farm. I checked the car and thought i better top up the tank before going too much further, so I drove on down to the pump. As it was a long journey and my beat up little truck was not up to the try, I hired a car and it took me a good few minutes to work out if I was driving a petrol or diesel car. Just as I was filling up, a stranger walked up to me asking for change. I thought what was the worst that could happen, so handed over the loose change I had. Very politely he thanked for my kindness, little did I know this was going to set off a chain of events I could never have imagined.

I wanted to have some fun while I was off work. I wanted to make a rocket so I got some petrol. I was lucky as I nearly get diesel. Anyway, I put a few drops of petrol in a plastic bottle and used a pump to vapourise the petrol. I put a match to the nosel of the bottle and it shot into the air.

She glanced at the red fuel warning on the dashboard and noticed the petrol was on the verge of running out. She swore under her breath - her boyfriend had promised to fill up with diesel the night before but, as usual he had forgotten. She remembered he came home, going on about how pumped he was for the concert tonight. His band hadn't been together that long and already they had several bookings. Trouble was, she was driving the van with their instruments and now she probably wasn't going to make it to the venue - he only had himself to blame.

Brian was a down on his luck kids football coach, he had to take training the following morning but last week all the kids complained because most of the footballs he had in his bag were flat, but he didn't have a pump to inflate them. He quickly jumped in his car to go to buy a pump, but broke down shortly after setting off because he'd put diesel in his car instead of petrol. He had to call a breakdown serive to come and pick him and his car up.

Marly stood staring at the petrol pump. "What the bloody hell do I put in this thing? There's no way to tell if it's petrol or diesel! I'll just try diesel in this hole at the back.". The horse's eyes grew huge and it neighed loudly.

Sally rode her horse down the canal. She knew her horse was running low on energy so needed to stop soon. She saw a barge selling a variety of things so decided to stop to see if she could refuel. Her pump style shoes were worn out so she had to stay atop her horse whilst speaking to the barge owner. She joked about her horse being neither petrol or diesel but infact, ran on carrots!

The motor coughed, jerked and the warning light flashed, jeez outta gas! It's a good five miles to the next town and its blowing a blizzard out there. This weather is due to set in for weeks, so I can't stay here. I've got a tank of diesel in the trunk for the tractor, so I'll have to use that. It'll ruin the petrol engine, but at least it will get me to the next town, or at least most of the way there. Hopefully they will will be able to pump and flush the engine before it is completely ruined.

Mischa and her family were going to collect their three new puppies. Mischa and her brother Tommy could not wait to see their little faces again. "What are we going to call the puppies?!" the siblings dad asked. "Petrol, Diesel and Pump!" Tommy beamed.

I had to put some diesel into my car as I was going on a long trip and needed to make sure that I was able to get there as quickly as possible without refuelling.  I went to the petrol station to get the diesel but there was a commotion happening at the pump that was free.  A crowd of people were gathered around all looking down towards the ground.  I got out of my car to see what was happening and what did I see, but a tiny kitten!!! Ginger and white and crying so loudly for all the size of it!! It was so cute but goodness, where did it come from?  .

A car mechanic had the surprise of his life when his wife gave birth to three babies instead of one! As he and his wife stared down at their three new children, the midwife stood behind them and asked a very valid question. "So, what will you call them?"   You see, they had a name for baby number one. They were naming him after his favourite WWF wrestler, Diesel. But the other two...? He began to sweat. With the pressure of both his wife and the midwives eyes on him, he blurted out the first two things he could think of.   "Their names are Diesel, Petrol and Pump!"  And that is the story of how their children got their very unique names. Thanks Dad.

I fell asleep with the price of petrol on my mind. Why? When I don't even drive a car? I went to work as usual on the bus but I could not get the question " Which is best for the environment petrol or diesel? out of my mind" As we passed the Petrol station I saw that the pump was surrounded by protestors.  I wondered if I should  join them?.

Samara sighed with annoyance. 'Water pumps given up again!' she muttered, cursing as she pulled the plastic container out of the way. Giving the lever a few good pulls for good measure, she left cursing, she was now going to have to make her way to town with what little petrol was left in the car. They didn't have the pennies for any of this and Alex would be back late, he was busy trying to sell the diesel they stole off the neighbouring farm last night. Theft was just the norm now, ever since the storms hit it was everyone for themselves. She did feel a twinge of guilt though, Bertie was old now and in no fit state to chase after thieves. Hence why they went there. They did pay him back in other ways, only last week, they shared a few spoonfuls of corn soup, nevermind it was because they couldn't stand another mouthful.

What happens when you put diesel into a petrol car? My friend and I decided to find out. He has a petrol car, and I a deisel one, and so we swopped fuels and strated the engine. We had to use our feet to pump the accelerator before anything happened. All seemed to be well, so we wondered why. It turned out we'd forgotten which car was which, and so each vehicle had its correct fuel.

The perfume shop was busy.  I couldn't decide on which aftershave to buy for my husband; petrol or diesel.  Thankfully, testers were available.  Petrol aroma was quite earthy, whilst Diesel had a floral undertone. But wait - what is this delightful smell?.. Pump!  Definitely the right choice for my husband!

Jim stepped foot into the car showroom and was browsing the various models and makes of vehicles available in his price range.  The manager approached Jim to enquire what kind of care he would like and whether it would suit his needs.  Jim explained that he previously had a Toyota RAV4 which was a diesel vehicle and as much as he loved his car, he told the manager of the car showroom that it kept breaking down and costing him money.  On further questioning by the manager, they both decided that due to Jim only doing short distances in his car, never driving distances or driving on the motorway, that a petrol car would be much more suited to his needs.  The manager explained how a diesel car needed long distance driving and was not really suitable for Jim's situation.  Jim finally signed off on a new petrol car, the manager agreed he could drive it off the lot that day if Jim was willing to pump the gas on the way home as it was low in fuel already. Jim readily agreed and happily drove his new car away, stopping to pump his new petrol vehicle on the way home.

the sun was shining, there was a gentle breeze and I was enjoying the drive through the countryside.   i was on my way to join other members of the Petrol Head Club for a fun day out.    I was wearing my favourite Diesel jeans and club T-shirt - i thought i looked great.    i switched radio channels to the Pump fm and sang alon

One evening, after a long trip to see family I was about to make my way to take the long drive home, around 2 hours away. I had had a fun time, but honestly I was just exhausted. Every step to the car felt like bliss, knowing I would soon be home and ready to sleep in my own bed. I opened the door and went to turn the keys, ready to leave, I would miss my family but it was time to make my own departure. I turned the keys, but rather than the usual hum I would expect to hear I just hear a harsh sound resonating from the engine. Something is wrong, this is not normal. I make my way out of the car and back to the house I had just moments ago been so delighted to depart from.  "Hey everyone, i'm back." I announced, with a twinge of disappointment in my voice. "It seems my car isn't starting, did anything happen to it while I was here?" "Well, actually" my youngest sibling spoke up. She had recently got a license of her own, so it was surprising she would be the one to speak up about issues with a car. "We don't have a station nearby, so I had hoped to help out a bit by pumping some of our own fuel in before you left!" There was a look of confusion across the family, no one sure what she meant by our own fuel. "Wait, you didn't specify. What kind of fuel was it?" I replied to her. "Oh! It was a canister of diesel, every car uses that nowadays, right?" she gleefully explained. There was a heavy silence across the room, especially on the adults. I took a breath before uttering "My car only uses petrol...".

Blazing past the obeying traffic, the getaway vehicle reached a peak speed of 80 mph on this enthralling police chase. Contrary to belief, this getaway vehicle was running low on gas. In a swift drift, the driver was able to get to the nearest petrol station. As he quickly got out to get the diesel pump, his clumsy friend accidently dropped his cigarette butt causing a mass fire, effectively ending the lives of these criminals on the spot.

A car spluttered to a stop of the motorway, the driver pulled over to the hard shoulder and exited the vehicle scratching their head. They looked around in disbelief as they realised their petrol cap had fallen off the car and petrol was leaking out onto the road. Now the tank was clearly drained and this had caused the car to splutter to a stop. The driver called the AA for assistance but the guy that arrived was new and nervous, he started to put diesel into the cars tank instead of petrol! Now once the driver realised the error he told the AA member to pump the diesel out so he could put petrol in instead.

A diesel train belts its way through the Highlands. The sun is starting to set and people on board feel sleepy after what seems like a never-ending journey. As the carriages attempt hard to pump their way to the top of the next peak, a strong stench of petrol seeps through the carriages. Smoke starts to bellow through the train as a fire has caught hold.

It was a rainy, dreary kind of day but just a normal one in England. I had a car full of petrol and I decided to take a drive out to the shopping centre; being outside today was not an option! As I was going round the bend just down the road, my car slipped on some spilt diesel. I went to pump my brakes but I ended up spinning out of control and crashed! Luckily I was not hurt so a day at home watching movies seemed the safer option.

As a vehicle owner and driver for over 40 years, I have been very fortunate to have owned a variety of different vehicles. I have not owned an electric vehicle, much to its early development and cost to purchase. I like the idea of helping the environment and utilising clean energy, but I'm afraid it is beyond my price point at this time. I therefore have only owned petrol or diesel cars which require the use of a pump to fill a tank rather than top up a battery.

The car was travelling too fast down the road. He couldn't keep control of the vehicle and he felt panic run through his veins. And in a flash, he had careered into the barriers where the stop and pump was smashed into it. Petrol and diesel was flung everywhere.

Marc was, as his friends would describe him, a 'petrol head': he loved cars, motorbikes, trucks, pretty much anything that looked good and could hit high speeds. When Marc graduated university, he moved to a small town and adopted a dog, named Diesel, to keep him company. Marc and Diesel would drive around the town in Marc's Ford Mustang, listening to rock music, with the windows down. Let's pump up the volume! Marc shouted to Diesel as they drove away into the sunset.

Once upon a time there was an elderly woman who lived on a canal barge. People did not know her well, as she kept to herself. Every morning she would start the diesel engine to generate electricity and heat her boat. The people on the farm where she stayed got used to hearing the chugging noise of the engine in the morning and would turn to each other and say "that must be Martha again." Martha had grey hair and wore practical canvas trousers with a bright wool cardigan she had made herself. She wore glasses and people would see her up on deck with a mug of hot coffee at lunchtime. No one knew Martha's story, only that she had arrived at the farm mooring, paid her rent for a year and had stayed every year for at least 10 years. One winter's day, Martha woke up to find water leaking into her boat. She immediately started the engine to get the bilge pump started but realised that she had forgotten to get petrol the last time she took a trip to town.

Daisy was worried about the water pump on her 90s era diesel pickup truck. "Don't worry so much," her husband told her, "if anything was wrong we'd know by now!" The truck immediately started to splutter and cough with a an ominous rattle. "I don't know what's wrong I filled it up all the way with petrol!" Her husband just stared.

On a sunny Saturday afternoon, my husband decided we could try and work on getting the long- forgotten project of installing a pump to assist with the borehole that was set up a couple of years back but never used since. Searching through the box that had documents on the setup, I simply could not find the manual. my husband was convinced it was a diesel pump but I strongly remember complaining that petrol prices were too high and almost definite that it was a petrol pump. The battle to figure out which of the two was correct was made harder as we realised that our internet was down. This was going to be a test of the best engineer in the house!

It was still another 10 miles to the next petrol or diesel pump. I didn't even know what this old battered car took but whatever it was it was running on fumes. I'd soon know about it if it was diesel as i think i heard once that you cant let a diesel tank run drive or the engine would go kaput. Every extra mile the car got was one fewer to the safety and one more away them.

I wondered about the puddle of petrol outside my house, near the front door. Had it have been diesel, I would have been less worried. The problem was that I had no idea whether the fuel pump in my vehicle was faulty ot not; the alternative was that someone was out to get me. Although I had few enemies, I knew the most likely culprit, but she was overseas on vacation. Knowing that, I scattered sand on the puddle and stopped worrying.

Whenever I thought of him. It was always with a sense of pain and contemplation. Did he really have to travel that night? Into the eerie void. With little concern that the choices he made to fill up at the station and take the precarious route would ensure his finality. We were told the car went up in flames when he crashed into the oak tree. His petrol tank was full. The tree remained stoic. It could have been diesel, it would have made little difference to the outcome. We told him not to leave. To drive to the petrol station. It's ironic. That a pump. A vessel used so commonly could be the source of his demise. I could not view the mangled metal visage

Once upon a time, there were three sentient cars, called Petrol, Diesel and Pump. Petrol was a red sporty car who loved to drive fast. Diesel was older, brown and reliable. Pump was a small silver car. They loved to drive around together and have adventures. However, Petrol was always getting cross at Diesel and Pump for not being able to drive as fast as he could. They decided to teach him a lesson. One day, they drove and drove and drove for as long as they could. Petrol felt himself running out of fuel and begged them to stop and wait. They carried on and left him behind at the side of the road. After a little while, they returned and found him feeling very sorry for himself. "See?" they told him, "we may be older and smaller, but we are still good, st and reliable

Unsure which vehicle to purchase from the sparkling showroom, I decided to take a seat in the waiting area, with a coffee to decide. There were both pros and cons to either a petrol or diesel powered vehicle. After careful consideration and finally purchasing my new vehicle, the day had arrived to collect from the showroom. Leaving the forecourt and driving down the road, the underinflated tyre pressure light 'pinged' on the dashboard. Before returning home I nipped into the local garage to inflate the tyre with an air pump to ensure the car was maintained.

One snowy evening, I set off in my mini cooper to my grandparents house, the journey was around 2 hours in length, about half way through i needed to stop to get some fuel. I had a strange loss of my senses and when I got to the pump i had forgotten whether the car took petrol or diesel, in my moment of madness i filled up the car with the wrong type of fuel! I sadly didn't realise until a few minutes into my journey after setting off ahain

My name is Diesel, Diesel Harcourt. A lot of people ask me where the inspiration for Diesel came from. My mother gave birth to me at the petrol station. She was 38.5 weeks pregnant, and I was not supposed to arrive for another 10 or so days. My father had taken her out for dinner at their favorite restaurant and they had stopped for gas along the way. Just as he'd gotten out and was lifting the pump, he heard her calling out for him. "I think my water just broke!"

As the day grows darker and I find myself having to do the weekly shopping it is with glee that I look over my shoulder whilst driving past a petrol pump. What a relic of the recent past, having had to put diesel in my old car and feeling like a slave to the big oil corporations that are stuck in their ways. Nowadays, I go shopping whilst my electric car charges, giving me time and not worrying what my actions impact our environment. To all the naysayers I say just this, don't wack it before you try it.

I was wearing my favourite pumps. I managed to walk through diesel  and get it on the sole of one pump and leave footprints all over my friend's carpet. It's impossible to get out. Even worse than petrol.
